                                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.—<name type="person">Private John G. Colgan</name>, <name type="organization">Co. F, 5th New
                                                                Jersey Volunteers</name>, aged 22 years, was wounded at
                                                                the battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="257">Chancellorsville, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1863-05-03">May 3d,
                                                                                1863</date>, by a piece of shell, which struck the upper
                                                  portion of the frontal bone, causing a fracture
                                                  with depression. He was conveyed to Washington,
                                                  and on <date type="admit" when="1863-05-09">May 9th</date> admitted to <name type="hospital" key="173">Harewood Hospital</name>,
                                                  where the trephine was applied, and the depressed
                                                  portion of bone removed. On May 30th, the wound
                                                  was doing well, and on <date type="transfer" when="1863-06-24">June 24th, 1863</date>, the
                                                  patient was transferred to <name type="hospital">Satterlee Hospital,
                                                                  Philadelphia</name>, where he was assigned to the <name type="organization">2d
                                                                                  battalion, Veteran Reserve Corp</name>s. This soldier was
                                                                discharged the service <date type="servicedischarge" when="1865-11-22">November 22d, 1865</date>, and
                                                  pensioned. There was a large cicatrix, with
                                                  depression from loss of the outer table of the <hi rend="italic">os frontis</hi>, near the junction of the coronal and
                                                  sagittal sutures, with tenderness upon pressure,
                                                  and the patient complained of vertigo when exposed
                                                  to the sun, or when undergoing active exercise.
                                                  His disability is rated one-half, and probably
                                                  permanent.</p>
                                                
